Don't worry.

453
00:35:23,087 --> 00:35:26,657
Now, Howard.
Now, Howard, Howard. Howard.

454
00:35:26,762 --> 00:35:30,161
If you're seriously talking about putting
carnality back on the silver screen,

455
00:35:30,265 --> 00:35:34,835
you must swear to let me in
on the casting sessions.

456
00:35:36,722 --> 00:35:39,919
I've somewhat of an eye -
an eye for talent, isn't that right, Johnny?

457
00:35:40,023 --> 00:35:42,592
You ought to give up that prancing
in tights, be a talent scout.

458
00:35:42,696 --> 00:35:46,887
That prancing in tights paid for my new
yacht. You must all come sailing with me.

459
00:35:46,991 --> 00:35:48,556
Catalina, this weekend.
What do you say?

460
00:35:48,661 --> 00:35:50,887
- Yeah, Catalina. Sounds grand.
- Let's have some fun.

461
00:35:50,991 --> 00:35:53,645
I've even managed to coax
the luscious Miss de Havilland

462
00:35:53,749 --> 00:35:56,019
and her equally luscious sister
to accompany me.

463
00:35:56,123 --> 00:35:58,337
Though I fear their mother
will insist on coming along

464
00:35:58,441 --> 00:36:00,941
to preserve their questionable virtue.

465
00:36:01,045 --> 00:36:05,738
We shall assault these twin monuments
of pristine Britannic beauty nonetheless.

466
00:36:05,842 --> 00:36:07,987
- What do you say, Howard?
- Yeah?

467
00:36:08,092 --> 00:36:09,490
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

468
00:36:09,594 --> 00:36:10,594
Yeah.

469
00:36:14,927 --> 00:36:17,247
I gotta... I gotta go.

470
00:36:17,351 --> 00:36:20,543
If you'll excuse us,
we have to be somewhere.

471
00:36:20,647 --> 00:36:23,420
You are somewhere, Howard,
you madman.

472
00:36:23,525 --> 00:36:26,549
- Somewhere else. Excuse us.
- Charmed, gentlemen.

473
00:36:26,653 --> 00:36:30,931
Do help yourself to the poached pears.
I hear they're divine.

474
00:36:31,035 --> 00:36:34,556
Well. Howard Hughes,
ladies and gentlemen.

475
00:36:34,660 --> 00:36:35,976
Was that meant for me?

476
00:36:36,080 --> 00:36:39,519
My hero.
God, all that Hollywood talk bores me silly.

477
00:36:39,623 --> 00:36:42,652
As if there aren't more important things
in the world. Mussolini, for one.

478
00:36:42,756 --> 00:36:46,822
- Where are we going, by the way?
- Do you feel like a little adventure?

479
00:36:46,926 --> 00:36:48,948
Do your worst, Mr Hughes.

480
00:36:49,052 --> 00:36:50,320
...you limey bastard.

481
00:36:50,425 --> 00:36:53,284
I'm a Tasmanian bastard,
you ignorant prick.

482
00:36:53,388 --> 00:36:55,458
That a way, Errol.

483
00:37:29,334 --> 00:37:32,114
That's Mr Mayer's house right there.

484
00:37:32,218 --> 00:37:35,498
Do you know where Jack Warner lives?

485
00:37:43,432 --> 00:37:47,294
- What's that on the steering wheel?
- Cellophane.

486
00:37:47,398 --> 00:37:51,678
If you had any idea of the crap
that people carry around on their hands...

487
00:37:51,783 --> 00:37:54,093
What kind of crap?

488
00:37:54,198 --> 00:37:56,399
You don't want to know.

489
00:38:01,033 --> 00:38:03,903
Hold onto the wheel for a bit.

490
00:38:11,209 --> 00:38:13,451
That's too hard.
Relax your hand. Relax your hand.

491
00:38:19,927 --> 00:38:25,082
You see, you've got to feel the vibration
of the engine through your fingertips.

492
00:38:25,186 --> 00:38:28,545
- Feel that?
- Yes.

493
00:38:28,649 --> 00:38:29,649
Yeah.

494
00:38:30,779 --> 00:38:32,969
Well, that's good.

495
00:38:33,073 --> 00:38:34,273
Golly.

496
00:38:39,237 --> 00:38:41,140
Well, she's all yours.

497
00:38:41,245 --> 00:38:45,729
- Where are you going?
- I think there's some milk back here.

498
00:38:45,834 --> 00:38:49,742
- You just keep us steady now.
- All right.

499
00:39:07,766 --> 00:39:09,548
- Howard.
- Yeah?

500
00:39:09,652 --> 00:39:12,045
There's a rather alarming mountain
heading our way.

501
00:39:12,150 --> 00:39:15,016
Pull back on the wheel a smidge.
Go on.

502
00:39:19,611 --> 00:39:20,811
Golly.

503
00:39:28,161 --> 00:39:33,867
I don't think I've ever met someone
who actually uses the word "golly".

504
00:39:40,257 --> 00:39:42,537
You all right?
Do you want me to take over?

505
00:39:42,642 --> 00:39:46,502
Just when I'm getting the hang of it?

506
00:39:50,309 --> 00:39:54,258
- You... You want some milk?
- Please.

507
00:40:15,959 --> 00:40:19,866
Utterly smashing.
We'll do it again. I'm free Wednesday.

508
00:40:19,971 --> 00:40:21,830
It's a little early for golf, though,
don't you think?

509
00:40:21,934 --> 00:40:24,289
Oh, no. I live right there.

510
00:40:24,394 --> 00:40:27,219
- Feel like a drink?
- Lead on.

511
00:40:28,263 --> 00:40:31,793
Now, that makes
for a challenging par four.

512
00:40:31,897 --> 00:40:36,009
My decorator picked out
the wallpaper and such.

513
00:40:36,114 --> 00:40:41,221
He's queer as a bed bug, but...
I just hate this room.

514
00:40:41,325 --> 00:40:43,555
Gives me the willies. Ugh.

515
00:40:43,659 --> 00:40:47,817
Feel I'm about to be swallowed up
by the latest issue of <i>Town & Country.</i>

516
00:40:56,375 --> 00:40:59,405
What room do you like?

517
00:40:59,509 --> 00:41:01,309
My study.

518
00:41:03,257 --> 00:41:05,333
Take me there.

519
00:41:21,441 --> 00:41:25,182
You are the tallest woman I know.

520
00:41:25,286 --> 00:41:27,893
And all sharp elbows and knees.

521
00:41:27,997 --> 00:41:29,397
Beware.

522
00:41:51,972 --> 00:41:55,008
Will you fly me to work tomorrow?

523
00:41:57,603 --> 00:42:00,438
It is tomorrow.

524
00:42:52,366 --> 00:42:54,064
Keep your eye on the fuel gauge.

525
00:42:54,168 --> 00:42:57,772
She's got a minimum of fuel to keep
her weight down. Two runs, that's it.

526
00:42:57,876 --> 00:43:00,926
After that, you're flying on vapours.
And then you crash and then you die.

527
00:43:01,031 --> 00:43:02,698
- Right.
- Just give her easy flying.

528
00:43:02,802 --> 00:43:05,656
Don't worry about speed.
And don't think about the record today.

529
00:43:05,760 --> 00:43:09,101
I wish to God you'd let someone else take
her up. You've got damn 20 test pilots...

530
00:43:09,205 --> 00:43:12,166
Hell, why should I let
someone else have all the fun?

531
00:43:12,270 --> 00:43:15,048
See you in a bit.

532
00:43:35,075 --> 00:43:36,675
Contact.

533
00:45:04,414 --> 00:45:06,214
Whoo-hoo.

534
00:45:06,550 --> 00:45:07,350
339.

535
00:45:09,711 --> 00:45:10,874
Goddamn.

536
00:45:33,318 --> 00:45:34,118
347.

537
00:45:35,454 --> 00:45:37,687
Whoo.
Son of a bitch.

538
00:46:10,147 --> 00:46:12,747
- 352.
- 352.

539
00:46:13,900 --> 00:46:15,145
Good girl.

540
00:46:24,745 --> 00:46:26,345
Damn it.

541
00:46:30,250 --> 00:46:33,447
Goddamn it.
Oh, God.

542
00:46:33,551 --> 00:46:37,044
- There goes our meal ticket.
- Come on.

543
00:47:16,922 --> 00:47:19,202
Howard. Howard.

544
00:47:19,307 --> 00:47:21,746
How did we do?

545
00:47:21,851 --> 00:47:25,789
352 on the last run.

546
00:47:25,893 --> 00:47:27,597
She'll go faster.

547
00:47:28,100 --> 00:47:30,380
Country mouse.

548
00:47:30,484 --> 00:47:31,964
Kate. Katie.

549
00:47:32,068 --> 00:47:34,138
Upstairs, city mouse.

550
00:47:36,817 --> 00:47:38,017
Hello.

551
00:47:38,286 --> 00:47:42,516
- Good Lord, what happened to you?
- Nothing. Hard landing. I cut my foot.

552
00:47:42,620 --> 00:47:45,477
Sit down. I'll take care of it.
You tell me everything.

553
00:47:45,582 --> 00:47:49,316
Well, you cannot imagine what it was like,
Katie. You cannot imagine the speed.

554
00:47:49,420 --> 00:47:51,482
She was like a winged bullet up there.

555
00:47:51,587 --> 00:47:55,654
- What did she make?
- Around...

556
00:47:55,759 --> 00:47:56,559
352.

557
00:48:04,177 --> 00:48:06,377
You did it.

558
00:48:06,941 --> 00:48:08,878
Fastest man on the planet.

559
00:48:08,982 --> 00:48:13,425
- Hot dog. I'm so proud of you.
- She did it, baby.

560
00:48:13,529 --> 00:48:17,055
- You knew she would.
- She was fine. She was just fine.

561
00:48:19,192 --> 00:48:21,648
- Now let me see your foot.
- Yeah.

562
00:48:22,613 --> 00:48:24,395
Good God.
You're covered in blood.

563
00:48:24,499 --> 00:48:27,686
No, no. That's just beet juice.
I crashed into a beet field.

564
00:48:27,791 --> 00:48:31,616
- What?
- Yeah, I crashed in a beet field.

565
00:48:34,124 --> 00:48:37,032
Let me get you cleaned up.

566
00:48:37,136 --> 00:48:39,242
Heavens, what is this?
Electrical tape?

567
00:48:39,346 --> 00:48:42,700
Yeah. Odie just sort of slammed it on there.

568
00:48:42,805 --> 00:48:48,838
But all I could think about was
getting home to see you.

569
00:48:52,476 --> 00:48:56,094
I am so proud of you.

570
00:48:59,900 --> 00:49:01,970
Now, this is going to sting a little bit.

571
00:49:02,074 --> 00:49:06,481
This is useless. Come to the bathroom.

572
00:49:07,532 --> 00:49:10,312
- Don't get beet juice on the carpet.
- I won't.

573
00:49:10,417 --> 00:49:13,245
- Too hot.
- Don't be a baby.

574
00:49:14,873 --> 00:49:18,448
Was the press there?

575
00:49:18,552 --> 00:49:20,952
Some, but...

576
00:49:21,880 --> 00:49:26,423
They're calling everyone.
Should be on the wires by now.

577
00:49:33,767 --> 00:49:35,967
What is it?

578
00:49:38,188 --> 00:49:39,188
Kate?

579
00:49:42,901 --> 00:49:46,431
I've been famous,
for better or worse,

580
00:49:46,535 --> 00:49:49,365
for a long time now, and...

581
00:49:50,826 --> 00:49:55,535
I wonder if you know
what it really means.

582
00:49:56,623 --> 00:50:00,447
Yeah. I had my fair share
of press on <i>Hell's Angels.</i>

583
00:50:00,551 --> 00:50:02,916
I'm used to it.

584
00:50:04,256 --> 00:50:05,856
Are you?

585
00:50:09,636 --> 00:50:11,712
Howard, we're...

586
00:50:14,349 --> 00:50:17,101
We're not like everyone else.

587
00:50:18,854 --> 00:50:24,431
Too many acute angles.
Too many eccentricities.

588
00:50:24,536 --> 00:50:29,765
We have to be very careful
not to let people in,

589
00:50:29,869 --> 00:50:32,819
or they'll make us into freaks.

590
00:50:33,785 --> 00:50:34,785
Kate.

591
00:50:35,837 --> 00:50:38,776
They can't get in here.
We're safe.

592
00:50:38,880 --> 00:50:41,910
They can always get in.

593
00:50:44,087 --> 00:50:47,539
When my brother killed himself,

594
00:50:48,592 --> 00:50:52,205
there were photographers at the funeral.

595
00:50:52,309 --> 00:50:55,221
There's no decency to it.

596
00:51:07,194 --> 00:51:09,103
You know, sometimes I...

597
00:51:12,783 --> 00:51:15,404
I get these feelings, Katie.

598
00:51:19,957 --> 00:51:22,827
I get these ideas, these...

599
00:51:25,379 --> 00:51:27,751
crazy ideas about...

600
00:51:30,300 --> 00:51:33,052
things that may not...

601
00:51:34,096 --> 00:51:37,458
things that may not really be there.

602
00:51:37,563 --> 00:51:38,563
Yeah.

603
00:51:45,774 --> 00:51:49,060
Sometimes I truly fear that I'm...

604
00:51:50,529 --> 00:51:53,529
losing my mind.

605
00:52:00,163 --> 00:52:02,654
And if I did, it would...

606
00:52:05,127 --> 00:52:08,044
It'd be like flying blind.

607
00:52:15,762 --> 00:52:18,762
You understand?

608
00:52:21,476 --> 00:52:24,596
You taught me to fly, Howard.

609
00:52:27,274 --> 00:52:29,765
I'll take the wheel.

610
00:52:44,958 --> 00:52:49,243
Smashing all records, Howard Hughes
outdoes Jules Verne's wildest dreams.

611
00:52:49,347 --> 00:52:52,495
Around the world from New York
to New York in four days,

612
00:52:52,599 --> 00:52:55,915
even beating Wiley Post's mark
by over three days.

613
00:52:56,019 --> 00:52:57,626
New aviation history is written

614
00:52:57,730 --> 00:53:01,461
when his Lockheed monoplane
returns swiftly and safely.

615
00:53:01,565 --> 00:53:05,631
A daring aviator.
A true pioneer of the world's airways.

616
00:53:05,735 --> 00:53:08,509
From New York to Paris,
he cuts Lindbergh's time in half.

617
00:53:08,613 --> 00:53:09,928
Then on to Moscow.

618
00:53:10,032 --> 00:53:14,559
35 hours out of New York, he roars
across Siberia's trackless wastes.

619
00:53:14,663 --> 00:53:19,272
60 hours out of New York, he heads
for Alaska, most hazardous hop of all.

620
00:53:19,376 --> 00:53:21,898
Continuing the terrific pace,
he comes home,

621
00:53:22,003 --> 00:53:24,481
bringing new laurels
to American aviation.

622
00:53:24,585 --> 00:53:28,994
Howard Hughes and his crew may find
more worlds to conq...

623
00:53:35,550 --> 00:53:37,938
You're not gonna believe this.
It just came across the wires.

624
00:53:38,043 --> 00:53:41,504
Howard Hughes
has bought control of TWA.

625
00:53:43,100 --> 00:53:46,008
I thought Mr Hughes
was flying around the world.

626
00:53:46,112 --> 00:53:51,097
Apparently, he did it while he was flying,
over the radio.

627
00:53:56,822 --> 00:54:01,606
I have heard some disquieting rumours
about Mr Hughes.

628
00:54:01,710 --> 00:54:06,411
I'd like to know everything
there is to know about Mr Hughes.

629
00:54:07,457 --> 00:54:11,669
I'd like you to attend
to that for me, thoroughly.

630
00:54:12,796 --> 00:54:15,410
Ah, the Pantages is glittering tonight.

631
00:54:15,514 --> 00:54:17,770
Right over here, Mr Hughes.
This way, over to the left.

632
00:54:17,874 --> 00:54:19,874
Mr Hughes. Mr Hughes,
how was your flight?

633
00:54:19,978 --> 00:54:22,358
Miss Hepburn, Miss Hepburn.
When are you gonna name the day?

634
00:54:22,462 --> 00:54:26,338
- Right over here, Mr Hughes.
- What's your next movie, Howard?

635
00:54:26,442 --> 00:54:30,048
Right here, Howard. How many more
records are you gonna set?

636
00:54:30,152 --> 00:54:34,092
Come on, Howard.
Give us a smile. It won't kill you.

637
00:54:34,197 --> 00:54:36,267
- Raise your head a little.
- Over here. Over here.

638
00:54:36,372 --> 00:54:38,018
Don't forget this side.

639
00:54:38,122 --> 00:54:40,271
Mr Hughes, when are you
gonna fly round the world again?

640
00:54:40,376 --> 00:54:44,233
You going to fly with Kate next time?
Did you get Ionely without her?

641
00:54:44,337 --> 00:54:46,778
Did you talk to Lindbergh
about your round-the-world flight yet?

642
00:54:46,882 --> 00:54:49,693
Mr Hughes,
where is Linda Darnell tonight?

643
00:54:49,798 --> 00:54:51,945
Right here.
Right here, Mr Hughes. That's it.

644
00:54:52,049 --> 00:54:55,284
Are you trying to be
more famous than Lindbergh?

645
00:54:55,389 --> 00:54:59,248
You know,
fame is supposed to be my turf.

646
00:55:01,261 --> 00:55:01,861
LB.

647
00:55:05,599 --> 00:55:08,296
If you don't get more distinguished
every time I see you.

648
00:55:08,401 --> 00:55:11,180
Ah, you look so beautiful.

649
00:55:19,029 --> 00:55:20,644
Is that true?

650
00:55:20,748 --> 00:55:25,116
...Mr Randolph Scott.
They make a handsome couple...

651
00:55:29,331 --> 00:55:31,195
Don't worry about it, Howard.

652
00:55:31,300 --> 00:55:33,406
She's just working the room.

653
00:55:33,510 --> 00:55:35,874
It's her job, baby.

654
00:55:37,172 --> 00:55:41,789
Sultry southern tigress
Ava Gardner dazzles the room tonight.

655
00:55:41,893 --> 00:55:46,761
She's the newest star in the MGM galaxy.
And believe you me...

656
00:55:50,310 --> 00:55:55,103
Jane Eyre has been selling
popcorn for over a hundred years, LB.

657
00:56:36,732 --> 00:56:37,932
Hello.

658
00:56:39,818 --> 00:56:41,018
Hello.

659
00:56:46,491 --> 00:56:49,327
Could you reach me a towel?

660
00:56:56,793 --> 00:56:57,593
I...

661
00:56:59,678 --> 00:57:02,957
I really can't do that.

662
00:57:04,551 --> 00:57:06,551
I'm sorry.

663
00:57:30,827 --> 00:57:35,400
I'm an idiot.
I'm a complete idiot and I'm sorry.

664
00:57:35,504 --> 00:57:36,608
- Forget it.
- No, no.

665
00:57:36,712 --> 00:57:41,031
I'm a vain, preening ass
without a single redeeming feature.

666
00:57:41,136 --> 00:57:44,742
That's not true.
You have very good teeth.

667
00:57:44,847 --> 00:57:46,447
Come on.

668
00:57:47,099 --> 00:57:49,330
I've got a better idea.
Take me flying.

669
00:57:49,435 --> 00:57:53,379
- Or better yet, I'll take you flying.
- Do your worst, Miss Hepburn.

670
00:58:01,900 --> 00:58:04,220
Don't be so squirmy, Howard.

671
00:58:04,324 --> 00:58:06,436
You're going to get on famously
with Father and Mother.

672
00:58:06,540 --> 00:58:10,277
And I'm sure they'll like you, too.
Once they get to know you.

673
00:58:18,375 --> 00:58:19,568
Hello. Hello.

674
00:58:19,672 --> 00:58:22,585
- Kath, hello.
- Kathy.

675
00:58:26,133 --> 00:58:28,062
Sweetheart, who's that
with the camera right there?

676
00:58:28,166 --> 00:58:32,002
That's my ex-husband, Ludlow. Father
and Mother are just mad about Luddie.

677
00:58:32,106 --> 00:58:34,877
What the hell is he doing here?

678
00:58:34,981 --> 00:58:37,339
He's here all the time.

679
00:58:37,443 --> 00:58:38,643
Hello.

680
00:58:40,647 --> 00:58:43,555
Sorry we're late. Mom.

681
00:58:43,660 --> 00:58:45,304
- Thank you.
- Dad.

682
00:58:45,408 --> 00:58:47,682
- Darling.
- Uncle Willy.

683
00:58:47,787 --> 00:58:51,270
Who've we got here?
Don't feel self-conscious.

684
00:58:51,375 --> 00:58:54,396
Hepburns. Hepburns.
Attention, please.

685
00:58:54,501 --> 00:58:56,858
This is Howard.

686
00:58:56,963 --> 00:59:00,069
Howard, welcome.

687
00:59:00,173 --> 00:59:02,705
Don't worry, he's had his lunch.

688
00:59:03,795 --> 00:59:05,993
He likes you.
That's unusual.

689
00:59:06,098 --> 00:59:09,247
We pay our devotion to the arts here.
A colony we created.

690
00:59:09,351 --> 00:59:11,957
Julian's a painter.
Abstract, of course.

691
00:59:12,061 --> 00:59:14,066
What the hell's the point
of painting something real

692
00:59:14,170 --> 00:59:16,961
when you can just take a picture
nowadays, don't you agree?

693
00:59:17,065 --> 00:59:19,967
Where do you stand on politics,
Mr Hughes?

694
00:59:20,071 --> 00:59:22,509
- Excuse me?
- We're all socialists here.

695
00:59:22,613 --> 00:59:24,813
We are not.

696
00:59:25,279 --> 00:59:27,980
You've met Mr Roosevelt.
