01:14:18,335 --> 01:14:21,040
Bob, you got something on your suit.

925
01:14:22,297 --> 01:14:23,297
Yeah.

926
01:14:24,055 --> 01:14:28,628
On your lapel there.
You got something on your lapel.

927
01:14:29,680 --> 01:14:31,756
Right there, Bob.

928
01:14:33,350 --> 01:14:37,007
You missed it.
Right there.

929
01:14:37,111 --> 01:14:39,218
Clean it off, would you?

930
01:14:39,323 --> 01:14:41,923
Here. Thanks.

931
01:14:45,070 --> 01:14:48,071
Now throw it away.

932
01:14:50,617 --> 01:14:53,155
No, over there.

933
01:14:58,417 --> 01:15:02,407
Thanks.
So, what do you call her?

934
01:15:02,511 --> 01:15:04,784
The Constellation.
But we can change that.

935
01:15:04,889 --> 01:15:06,663
No, no, no.

936
01:15:06,768 --> 01:15:09,428
It's pretty. I like her.

937
01:15:10,596 --> 01:15:14,586
So, what kind of deal can you give me?
What kind of deal can you give me?

938
01:15:14,690 --> 01:15:17,252
We'll give you the first 40 planes
off the assembly line.

939
01:15:17,356 --> 01:15:19,838
That should give us
about two years exclusivity with her?

940
01:15:19,942 --> 01:15:21,387
Hell, more than that.

941
01:15:21,491 --> 01:15:25,554
United and American don't have
the imagination for a plane like this.

942
01:15:25,658 --> 01:15:28,772
Two years ahead of Juan Trippe, then.

943
01:15:33,327 --> 01:15:37,075
- How much?
- 450,000 each.

944
01:15:37,706 --> 01:15:41,446
That's 18 million for the first 40.

945
01:15:41,550 --> 01:15:47,000
Hell, TWA can't afford that.
The damn airline's flat broke.

946
01:15:48,675 --> 01:15:51,380
Guess I'll just have
to pay for them myself.

947
01:15:52,095 --> 01:15:55,209
Build them, Bob.
Send the bill to Noah Dietrich.

948
01:15:55,313 --> 01:15:57,050
And thank you.

949
01:16:00,646 --> 01:16:02,632
Merry Christmas.

950
01:16:02,736 --> 01:16:06,360
You have just placed the largest order for
airplanes in the history of the damn planet.

951
01:16:07,235 --> 01:16:09,102
Lockheed just sent us a bill for $18 million.

952
01:16:09,206 --> 01:16:12,770
Now now, don't get all hysterical on me,
Noah. It isn't good for you.

953
01:16:12,874 --> 01:16:16,561
- This is a lot of money for some planes.
- Yes. Yes, I know it's a lot of money.

954
01:16:16,666 --> 01:16:20,318
It's too damn much. You think I've just got
$18 million in petty cash?

955
01:16:20,423 --> 01:16:22,490
I should have told you earlier.
It slipped my mind.

956
01:16:22,595 --> 01:16:25,201
- Slipped your mind? For God's sake.
- Right. Well, look...

957
01:16:25,306 --> 01:16:29,074
- How could $18 million slip your mind?
- I'll get back to you. Goodbye, now.

958
01:16:29,178 --> 01:16:32,424
Hey, honey.
What are you doing home?

959
01:16:36,682 --> 01:16:40,589
You're not one for tears
and, well, neither am I.

960
01:16:40,693 --> 01:16:44,137
So it's best to come out with it.

961
01:16:47,109 --> 01:16:51,854
I've met someone.
I've fallen in love and I'm moving out.

962
01:16:54,074 --> 01:16:58,730
If I could make it any more gentle, I would.

963
01:16:58,834 --> 01:17:01,234
But I can't.

964
01:17:01,547 --> 01:17:05,205
So there we both are.

965
01:17:09,506 --> 01:17:11,454
Let's be honest.

966
01:17:11,558 --> 01:17:16,040
It's all been a grand adventure,
but it couldn't possibly last.

967
01:17:16,144 --> 01:17:20,135
We're too alike, you and I.

968
01:17:22,144 --> 01:17:25,423
- You met someone?
- Someone more appropriate.

969
01:17:25,527 --> 01:17:27,728
To me, I mean.

970
01:17:30,402 --> 01:17:33,349
What does that mean,
more appropriate?

971
01:17:33,453 --> 01:17:38,019
Someone more attuned to my needs.

972
01:17:38,123 --> 01:17:41,736
Look at me, Katie.
Stop acting.

973
01:17:43,415 --> 01:17:45,491
I'm not acting.

974
01:17:50,130 --> 01:17:52,917
I wonder if you even know any more.

975
01:17:57,679 --> 01:17:59,755
Don't be unkind.

976
01:18:02,559 --> 01:18:03,759
You...

977
01:18:05,655 --> 01:18:08,655
You want to go?

978
01:18:10,609 --> 01:18:11,809
Go on.

979
01:18:13,160 --> 01:18:16,848
Actresses are cheap in this town, darling.
I got a lot of money.

980
01:18:16,953 --> 01:18:21,400
- Howard, please. This is beneath you.
- No, no, this is exactly me.

981
01:18:21,504 --> 01:18:24,404
You come in here out of the blue and
tell me you're leaving me just like that,

982
01:18:24,508 --> 01:18:26,733
and you have the nerve
to expect graciousness?

983
01:18:26,838 --> 01:18:32,283
I expect a little maturity. I expect you
to face the situation like an adult who...

984
01:18:32,387 --> 01:18:36,243
Don't talk down to me.
Don't you ever talk down to me.

985
01:18:36,347 --> 01:18:39,712
You are a movie star, nothing more.

986
01:19:51,752 --> 01:19:54,871
Don't answer it.

987
01:19:56,381 --> 01:19:58,246
What is it, Howard?

988
01:19:58,350 --> 01:20:00,350
Hey, Noah.

989
01:20:00,516 --> 01:20:03,751
I need you to get to Penney's
and buy me new clothes.

990
01:20:03,855 --> 01:20:05,878
- Penney's isn't open.
- Shit.

991
01:20:05,983 --> 01:20:10,297
- It's two in the morning.
- Yeah, that's right. Ah, well.

992
01:20:10,402 --> 01:20:11,886
First thing tomorrow, then, all right?

993
01:20:11,991 --> 01:20:15,010
I need two suits off the rack.
One light and one dark.

994
01:20:15,115 --> 01:20:18,555
Three white shirts and three pairs
of white tennis shoes. You got that?

995
01:20:18,659 --> 01:20:21,729
- Yeah.
- No, no. Make it Woolworths.

996
01:20:21,833 --> 01:20:25,353
- Woolworths.
- No, no. Penney's. Penney's.

997
01:20:25,457 --> 01:20:27,732
All right, then.

998
01:20:27,837 --> 01:20:31,320
I'll get into it as soon as I can, Howard.

999
01:20:31,425 --> 01:20:34,740
- Noah, do you have a recorder?
- No.

1000
01:20:34,845 --> 01:20:38,366
- Are you recording this conversation?
- No.

1001
01:20:38,470 --> 01:20:39,070
OK.

1002
01:20:40,268 --> 01:20:42,668
I trust you.

1003
01:20:42,810 --> 01:20:43,668
Howard...

1004
01:20:43,772 --> 01:20:46,542
Listen, I need those suits
first thing tomorrow, all right?

1005
01:20:46,646 --> 01:20:47,833
- All right.
- Wait, wait.

1006
01:20:47,937 --> 01:20:51,090
- Did I say Penney's or Woolworths?
- Penney's.

1007
01:20:51,194 --> 01:20:54,935
- Better make it Sears.
- All right, then. Sears.

1008
01:20:58,443 --> 01:21:00,519
I'm sorry, honey.

1009
01:21:01,780 --> 01:21:04,188
If I don't answer,
he'll just call back.

1010
01:21:25,762 --> 01:21:29,381
Stop there, if you please,
Miss Domergue.

1011
01:21:34,605 --> 01:21:38,428
Have you had surgery, Miss Domergue?

1012
01:21:38,532 --> 01:21:39,132
No.

1013
01:21:40,910 --> 01:21:44,153
Do you have scars of any kind?

1014
01:21:45,365 --> 01:21:45,965
No.

1015
01:21:48,577 --> 01:21:51,115
Wipe off your lipstick.

1016
01:21:55,292 --> 01:21:57,989
That's much better.

1017
01:21:58,094 --> 01:22:03,211
Now, you understand that you'd be
under contract to me, personally?

1018
01:22:04,009 --> 01:22:06,500
Do you know what that means?

1019
01:22:14,728 --> 01:22:17,433
Turn around for me.

1020
01:22:24,696 --> 01:22:26,696
Very nice.

1021
01:22:27,121 --> 01:22:29,441
You move well.

1022
01:22:31,745 --> 01:22:35,402
You live with your family, do you?

1023
01:22:35,506 --> 01:22:36,306
Yes.

1024
01:22:38,089 --> 01:22:40,489
That's nice.

1025
01:22:40,969 --> 01:22:43,909
Tell me something.

1026
01:22:44,014 --> 01:22:46,545
How old are you, Miss Domergue?

1027
01:22:49,263 --> 01:22:49,863
15.

1028
01:22:54,476 --> 01:22:56,801
Holy mother of God.

1029
01:23:15,122 --> 01:23:19,239
Well, a car picks me up
every morning at eight, and off I go.

1030
01:23:19,344 --> 01:23:25,161
I am getting my high-school diploma.
Howard thinks that education is important.

1031
01:23:25,265 --> 01:23:27,577
- That's right.
- And then after classes,

1032
01:23:27,681 --> 01:23:31,250
I'm off for elocution
and grooming and fittings.

1033
01:23:31,355 --> 01:23:33,422
Well, blow me down.

1034
01:23:34,516 --> 01:23:36,966
Don't tell me Pan Am's
working out of the Cocoanut Grove now?

1035
01:23:37,071 --> 01:23:39,008
- Hello, Jack.
- Hello, Juan.

1036
01:23:39,112 --> 01:23:40,758
Helen, good to see you.

1037
01:23:40,862 --> 01:23:43,470
- How are you, Howard?
- Good, thanks.

1038
01:23:43,574 --> 01:23:47,390
- This is Miss Faith Domergue.
- Sit down. Now, what you doing out here?

1039
01:23:47,495 --> 01:23:50,479
Well, I'm out this way to meet
with Douglas about the DC-4.

1040
01:23:50,583 --> 01:23:54,481
That's our new plane
and it is gonna be a pip, let me tell you.

1041
01:23:54,585 --> 01:23:58,024
- How's the Constellation coming?
- Good.

1042
01:23:58,128 --> 01:23:59,328
Great.

1043
01:24:00,675 --> 01:24:03,419
So, how about letting me steal a peek?

1044
01:24:05,255 --> 01:24:07,203
Don't think so.

1045
01:24:07,307 --> 01:24:11,161
You know, I should be cross with you.
You stole Ray Loewy from us.

1046
01:24:11,265 --> 01:24:13,128
He's doing our interior design.
That's right.

1047
01:24:13,232 --> 01:24:15,713
He was doing ours.

1048
01:24:17,267 --> 01:24:20,259
So, what are your colours?

1049
01:24:20,363 --> 01:24:22,145
Stop fishing.

1050
01:24:23,774 --> 01:24:27,930
So, you have buttons or zippers?

1051
01:24:28,034 --> 01:24:29,688
I'm sorry?

1052
01:24:31,490 --> 01:24:33,310
Buttons or zippers?

1053
01:24:33,415 --> 01:24:36,575
For the drapes on the sleeping berths.

1054
01:24:38,956 --> 01:24:40,556
Zippers.

1055
01:24:49,424 --> 01:24:51,024
Buttons?

1056
01:25:00,727 --> 01:25:03,802
So, I suppose you'll be
expanding on down to Mexico.

1057
01:25:03,907 --> 01:25:07,094
- Why do you say that?
- Well, your range is 3,000 miles.

1058
01:25:07,198 --> 01:25:10,139
I would imagine you'd expand
from Los Angeles to Mexico.

1059
01:25:10,243 --> 01:25:13,516
- And maybe on down to South America.
- Hey, that's a good idea.

1060
01:25:13,620 --> 01:25:17,067
- Anyone got a pen?
- Or across the Atlantic.

1061
01:25:19,246 --> 01:25:22,692
Now, honey, you've had enough of this
ice cream. You give me that spoon.

1062
01:25:22,796 --> 01:25:26,207
You don't want to get your gloves all sticky.

1063
01:25:27,254 --> 01:25:29,293
Isn't that too far?

1064
01:25:34,261 --> 01:25:37,926
New York to Newfoundland...

1065
01:25:39,182 --> 01:25:41,673
to Ireland...

1066
01:25:45,397 --> 01:25:47,197
to Paris.

1067
01:25:54,114 --> 01:25:55,114
Well,

1068
01:25:56,372 --> 01:26:00,567
Pan Am welcomes you.
We're overbooked as it is.

1069
01:26:00,672 --> 01:26:04,319
It's such a burden doing it all on your own,
let me tell you.

1070
01:26:04,423 --> 01:26:06,614
So, when's the Connie gonna be ready?

1071
01:26:06,718 --> 01:26:09,407
- Next year, maybe. DC-4?
- Next year.

1072
01:26:09,512 --> 01:26:12,784
Well, we look forward to her, then.

1073
01:26:12,888 --> 01:26:15,837
And I to the Connie.

1074
01:26:16,678 --> 01:26:20,585
I've ordered the next 40 after you.

1075
01:26:20,690 --> 01:26:22,003
It's Miss?

1076
01:26:22,108 --> 01:26:23,654
- Domergue.
- Domergue. Yes, of course.

1077
01:26:23,758 --> 01:26:26,302
Now, was that a rumba or a samba
you were doing out there, my dear?

1078
01:26:26,407 --> 01:26:29,343
- It was a samba.
- A samba, yes.

1079
01:26:29,447 --> 01:26:32,775
Howard, I never knew
you were such a good dancer.

1080
01:26:33,612 --> 01:26:35,854
Helen, Jack.

1081
01:26:37,282 --> 01:26:40,690
Good going, boss. You just gave away
our entire postwar strategy.

1082
01:26:40,794 --> 01:26:42,689
- He can't stop us.
- He's Pan Am, Howard.

1083
01:26:42,793 --> 01:26:45,076
He can stop anything.

1084
01:26:46,792 --> 01:26:48,575
Waiter, give me
the largest Scotch you've got.

1085
01:26:48,679 --> 01:26:53,289
I don't know what in the hell you're
so goddamn giddy about. Excuse me.

1086
01:28:44,409 --> 01:28:45,409
Jack.

1087
01:28:45,962 --> 01:28:48,570
All right. I want you to get in touch
with Mr Joyce and Mr Berg.

1088
01:28:48,674 --> 01:28:49,884
Those are my boys in Washington.

1089
01:28:49,988 --> 01:28:52,449
Set up a meeting with Jesse Jones,
he's the secretary of commerce.

1090
01:28:52,553 --> 01:28:53,949
- Old golfing buddy.
- Slow down.

1091
01:28:54,053 --> 01:28:56,446
We're gonna need terminals
in both Ireland and France,

1092
01:28:56,551 --> 01:28:57,975
and I want to get tax breaks from them.

1093
01:28:58,079 --> 01:29:01,038
If that shit-ass thinks that he owns
the entire goddamn world,

1094
01:29:01,143 --> 01:29:03,418
- he's got another think coming.
- Pan Am owns Europe, you know.

1095
01:29:03,522 --> 01:29:04,919
He's smart.
We ought to think about Mexico.

1096
01:29:05,024 --> 01:29:06,025
To hell with Mexico, Jack.

1097
01:29:06,129 --> 01:29:09,003
No one airline should have
a monopoly on flying the Atlantic.

1098
01:29:09,107 --> 01:29:12,592
For Christ's sakes, it isn't fair. Look,
he owns Pan Am. He owns Congress.

1099
01:29:12,696 --> 01:29:16,678
He owns the Civil Aeronautics Board,
but he does not own the sky.

1100
01:29:16,782 --> 01:29:19,768
We are in a street fight with that
son of a bitch now, and I'm not gonna lose.

1101
01:29:19,872 --> 01:29:23,224
I've been fighting high-hat, Ivy-League
pricks like him my whole goddamn life.

1102
01:29:23,328 --> 01:29:27,102
And listen, fire Ray Loewy.
You goddamn heard me? Fire Ray Loewy.

1103
01:29:27,206 --> 01:29:30,526
He's spying for Trippe. That shit-heel
knew all about the goddamn buttons.

1104
01:29:30,631 --> 01:29:34,620
Spies in my midst, Jack.
Spies in my midst.

1105
01:29:49,641 --> 01:29:53,093
- Hello, Howard.
- Roland.

1106
01:29:54,438 --> 01:29:57,889
So, what can I do for you?

1107
01:30:00,986 --> 01:30:05,020
I want all the pictures you have
of Kate Hepburn and Spencer Tracy.

1108
01:30:05,124 --> 01:30:08,728
All the negatives.
And I want you to kill the story.

1109
01:30:08,832 --> 01:30:12,235
Howard, he's a married man.
He's a Catholic.

1110
01:30:12,339 --> 01:30:16,280
They're both movie stars.
Fair game all around.

1111
01:30:23,091 --> 01:30:26,166
My office knows where I am, Howard.

1112
01:30:26,271 --> 01:30:29,169
I'm not gonna kill you, Roland.

1113
01:30:29,274 --> 01:30:31,720
I don't do that.

1114
01:30:35,938 --> 01:30:38,725
- How much?
- Not for sale.

1115
01:30:41,485 --> 01:30:43,285
How much?

1116
01:30:44,287 --> 01:30:46,887
Not for sale.

1117
01:30:50,661 --> 01:30:54,568
You ever cheat on your wife, Roland?

1118
01:30:54,672 --> 01:30:57,695
You ever screw a coloured girl?

1119
01:30:57,799 --> 01:31:01,209
You ever steal anything?
You ever hurt anyone?

1120
01:31:03,131 --> 01:31:05,329
Good night, Howard.

1121
01:31:05,434 --> 01:31:09,755
You ever go to
a Communist Party meeting, Roland?

1122
01:31:18,188 --> 01:31:20,188
TWA stock.

1123
01:31:21,406 --> 01:31:23,206
How much?

1124
01:31:24,245 --> 01:31:27,936
- 50,000 shares.
- Ten.

1125
01:31:30,867 --> 01:31:32,867
All right.

1126
01:31:35,497 --> 01:31:37,234
This isn't gonna be that easy.

1127
01:31:37,339 --> 01:31:40,907
He's been making big contributions
on both sides of the aisle.

1128
01:31:41,011 --> 01:31:44,616
And Jack Frye is out there lobbying
everybody in town.

1129
01:31:44,720 --> 01:31:48,749
The French and British ambassadors
are all lined up on his side now.

1130
01:31:48,853 --> 01:31:52,878
I'm telling you, TWA is serious
about going international.

1131
01:31:52,982 --> 01:31:57,757
OK. Point, Mr Hughes.
Very well. You know what I think?

1132
01:31:57,861 --> 01:32:00,512
I think it's time for you to introduce
the Community Airline Bill

1133
01:32:00,616 --> 01:32:02,928
on the floor of the Senate.

1134
01:32:03,032 --> 01:32:05,804
- Is it done?
- My people are finishing it right now.

1135
01:32:05,909 --> 01:32:12,023
I also have to get you on the committee
investigating the national defence.

1136
01:32:12,993 --> 01:32:16,234
On the committee or chairman?

1137
01:32:16,338 --> 01:32:19,109
You know, I could be
much more effective as chairman.

1138
01:32:19,214 --> 01:32:22,986
It's a great public platform.
You know, it generates a lot of press.

1139
01:32:23,091 --> 01:32:25,034
Wasn't Truman chairman
of that committee?

1140
01:32:25,138 --> 01:32:29,076
Yeah, right. Now he's vice president.
Look what he did with it.

1141
01:32:29,180 --> 01:32:31,980
No, I think...

1142
01:32:32,105 --> 01:32:34,581
I think chairman.

1143
01:32:34,685 --> 01:32:38,044
What do you think?

1144
01:32:38,148 --> 01:32:40,923
- Chairman. That is interesting.
- Yeah.

1145
01:32:41,027 --> 01:32:44,512
Let me show you these specs
for the DC-4.

1146
01:32:44,616 --> 01:32:48,348
Ava, what do you think about
"Trans World Airlines"?

1147
01:32:48,452 --> 01:32:50,931
"Transcontinental and Western"
just doesn't fit any more.

1148
01:32:51,035 --> 01:32:53,811
Now that we're international,
we need a name that reflects that.

1149
01:32:53,915 --> 01:32:56,772
"Trans World" is good.
Kind of peppy.

1150
01:32:56,876 --> 01:32:59,076
TWA. Right?

1151
01:32:59,544 --> 01:33:02,490
Keep the same initials. That way you
don't need to repaint any of the planes.

1152
01:33:02,595 --> 01:33:05,780
That's you, always pinching pennies.

1153
01:33:05,884 --> 01:33:07,955
Hand me my wrap.

1154
01:33:21,937 --> 01:33:24,226
Knock it off.

1155
01:33:30,320 --> 01:33:33,895
I have something for you.

1156
01:33:33,999 --> 01:33:35,999
Stay here.

1157
01:33:41,331 --> 01:33:44,111
- What the hell is this?
- It's a present.

1158
01:33:44,215 --> 01:33:47,323
Go on and open it.

1159
01:33:47,427 --> 01:33:50,828
A box of trash.
You shouldn't have.

1160
01:33:50,933 --> 01:33:53,498
Keep looking.
Keep looking.

1161
01:33:57,472 --> 01:34:00,464
